# Merge Equivalent DFA States

## Description

Applies Hopcroft's DFA minimization algorithm to the compiled
pattern automaton. DFA states with identical outgoing transitions
and identical acceptance status are merged, reducing the state
count and transition table size.

**When to apply**: After DFA compilation from the pattern, when
the compiled automaton has equivalent states. This is common when
patterns have alternations or when different DEFINE conditions
produce overlapping state sets during subset construction.

**Why it works**: Two DFA states are equivalent if they accept
the same set of future input strings. Hopcroft's algorithm
computes the minimal DFA in O(n log n) time, where n is the
number of states.

## Relational Algebra

```latex
-- Before: compiled DFA with redundant states
$$
RowPattern(
  ...,
  dfa: DFA {
    states: [S0, S1, S2, S3, S4],
    transitions: {
      S0 -[A]\rightarrow S1,
      S0 -[B]\rightarrow S2,
      S1 -[C]\rightarrow S3,
      S2 -[C]\rightarrow S3,  -- S1 and S2 have same out-transitions
    },
    accept: [S3]
  }
)
$$

-- After: minimized DFA (S1 and S2 merged)
$$
RowPattern(
  ...,
  dfa: DFA {
    states: [S0, S12, S3],
    transitions: {
      S0 -[A]\rightarrow S12,
      S0 -[B]\rightarrow S12,
      S12 -[C]\rightarrow S3,
    },
    accept: [S3]
  }
)
$$

```

## Implementation

```rust
use egg::{rewrite as rw, *};

// Trigger DFA minimization after compilation
rw!("rpr-minimize-dfa";
    "(row-pattern ?input ?partition ?order ?defines ?measures
       (compiled-dfa ?states ?transitions ?accept))" =>
    "(row-pattern ?input ?partition ?order ?defines ?measures
       (minimized-dfa (hopcroft-minimize ?states ?transitions ?accept)))"
    if dfa_has_equivalent_states("?states", "?transitions", "?accept")
),

// Merge states with identical DEFINE conditions
rw!("rpr-merge-define-equivalent-states";
    "(dfa-state ?s1 (transitions ?t1) (define ?cond))
     (dfa-state ?s2 (transitions ?t1) (define ?cond))" =>
    "(dfa-state ?s1 (transitions ?t1) (define ?cond))"
    if states_have_identical_transitions("?s1", "?s2")
),
```

## Algorithm

```rust
fn hopcroft_minimize(dfa: &DFA) -> DFA {
    // Hopcroft's partition refinement algorithm
    // 1. Initial partition: {accepting states} U {non-accepting states}
    // 2. For each partition P and input symbol a:
    //    Split partitions based on where transitions on 'a' lead.
    // 3. Repeat until no partition can be split.
    // 4. Each final partition becomes one state in the minimal DFA.

    let mut partitions = vec![
        dfa.accepting_states().clone(),
        dfa.non_accepting_states().clone(),
    ];
    let mut worklist: VecDeque<_> = partitions.iter().cloned().collect();

    while let Some(splitter) = worklist.pop_front() {
        for symbol in dfa.alphabet() {
            let preimage = dfa.preimage(&splitter, symbol);
            let mut new_partitions = Vec::new();

            for partition in &partitions {
                let intersection: HashSet<_> = partition
                    .intersection(&preimage).cloned().collect();
                let difference: HashSet<_> = partition
                    .difference(&preimage).cloned().collect();

                if !intersection.is_empty() && !difference.is_empty() {
                    new_partitions.push(intersection.clone());
                    new_partitions.push(difference.clone());
                    worklist.push_back(
                        if intersection.len() <= difference.len() {
                            intersection
                        } else {
                            difference
                        }
                    );
                } else {
                    new_partitions.push(partition.clone());
                }
            }
            partitions = new_partitions;
        }
    }

    build_minimal_dfa(&partitions, dfa)
}
```

## Preconditions

```rust
fn dfa_has_equivalent_states(
    states: &[State],
    transitions: &TransitionTable,
    accept: &HashSet<State>,
) -> bool {
    // Check if any two states have identical outgoing transitions
    // and same acceptance status.
    for i in 0..states.len() {
        for j in (i + 1)..states.len() {
            let same_accept = accept.contains(&states[i])
                == accept.contains(&states[j]);
            let same_trans = transitions.outgoing(&states[i])
                == transitions.outgoing(&states[j]);
            if same_accept && same_trans {
                return true;
            }
        }
    }
    false
}
```

**Restrictions:**
- Only applies to the compiled DFA, not the pattern AST.
- Must preserve pattern variable labels on transitions for MEASURES computation.
- Minimization must be done after all pattern simplification rules have been applied.

## Cost Model

```rust
fn estimated_benefit(
    original_states: usize,
    minimized_states: usize,
    input_card: f64,
) -> f64 {
    // Per-row cost is proportional to number of active states
    // (DFA has exactly one active state, but transition table
    // lookup cost scales with table size).
    let transition_table_before = original_states * original_states;
    let transition_table_after = minimized_states * minimized_states;

    let cache_benefit = if transition_table_after <= 64 { 0.1 } else { 0.0 };

    let state_reduction = (original_states - minimized_states) as f64
        / original_states as f64;
    state_reduction * 0.4 + cache_benefit
}
```

**Typical benefit**: 10-40%. Depends on pattern complexity and
amount of state duplication. Complex patterns with alternations
see the greatest reduction (20-40% state reduction).

## Test Cases

### Positive: alternation producing duplicate states

```sql
-- Pattern: (A B) | (A C)
-- NFA -> DFA may produce duplicate states for the A prefix.
-- After minimization: shared states for A.
MATCH_RECOGNIZE (
  PATTERN ((A B) | (A C))
  DEFINE
    A AS price > 100,
    B AS price > PREV(price),
    C AS volume > 1000000
)
```

### Positive: patterns with equivalent DEFINE conditions

```sql
-- A and B have the same DEFINE condition
-- DFA states for A-matching and B-matching are equivalent
MATCH_RECOGNIZE (
  PATTERN (A B)
  DEFINE
    A AS price > PREV(price),
    B AS price > PREV(price)
)
-- After minimization: A and B states merged (same behavior)
```

### Negative: all states already distinct

```sql
-- Every state has unique transitions (already minimal)
MATCH_RECOGNIZE (
  PATTERN (A B C)
  DEFINE
    A AS price > 100,
    B AS volume > 1000000,
    C AS price < 50
)
```

